      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>When a primary alcohol is treated with <i>p</i>-toluenesulfonyl chloride at room temperature in the presence of an organic base such as pyridine, a tosylate is formed. When the same reaction is carried out at higher temperature, an alkyl chloride is often formed. Explain.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdnNUIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--921d8357b030993f156335106fb9a8f74b066e91/OChem_11_EC_046.jpg\" alt=\"The reaction of benzyl alcohol with tosyl chloride and pyridine at 60 degrees Celsius yields benzyl chloride.\">",
